{"key":"post-13352208","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>13352208</id>\n<content>A living room is not appropriate for mushroom culturing with a flow hood.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The air from the flowhood is barely enough to bend a match flame over.&amp;nbsp; Air currents in a large room can easily be stronger than that, thus they blow contaminants right into your media.&amp;nbsp; In addition, you need to be wearing a surgical mask because your own breath is faster than the speed of the sterile airflow, resulting in bacteria contamination if you exhale or especially talk while making transfers.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Put the flowhood in a small closed room, and let it run for at least an hour before beginning work.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Culturing on agar from dry fruits is an advanced technique where even the experts fail a majority of the time.&amp;nbsp; I'd suggest working with fresh sterile cultures or spores.&amp;nbsp; Get an inoculating loop and flame it before use.&amp;nbsp; Transfer the minimum amount of spores possible to each dish.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>13355330</next>\n<prev>13352180</prev>\n<first>13350754</first>\n<last>13355844</last>\n<when>1287425851</when>\n<utime>10/18/10 09:17 PM</utime>\n</post>"}